    "Rule 4.1(a) prohibits a lawyer, in the course of representing a client, from knowingly making a false statement of material fact or law to a third person. Affirmatively asserting that a foundation has no known defects when the lawyer knows of an engineering report to the contrary is a false statement of material fact. Zealous advocacy permits hard bargaining and even non-disclosure in some settings, but it never permits a knowing, material lie to the other side.",
